The paper focuses on creating visual summaries of large time-varying data sets, which involves techniques for data visualization and analysis. The use of dimensionality-reduction techniques such as Principle Component Analysis, Sammon mapping, and t-SNE suggests a focus on graphics and visualization (cs.GR). The mention of "entities moving in 2D" suggests a focus on computer vision (cs.CV) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The use of quality metrics suggests a focus on multimedia (cs.MM) and information retrieval (cs.IR).
